WEBVTT

00:01.577 --> 00:03.836
<i> [soft music]</i>

00:03.912 --> 00:05.671
- Good morning.

00:05.748 --> 00:07.464
No. No, no, no.

00:08.901 --> 00:12.660
Good morning. Mm-hmm.

00:12.738 --> 00:14.905
That one.

00:14.907 --> 00:19.309
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

00:22.506 --> 00:23.838
Good morning.

00:23.858 --> 00:25.190
- Morning.

00:25.267 --> 00:28.252
- Um, how are you?
[chuckles]

00:28.270 --> 00:30.921
- I'm good.
Why are you acting weird?

00:30.923 --> 00:32.756
- I'm not acting weird.
[chuckles]

00:32.758 --> 00:34.107
I simply want to make sure
that you're fine.

00:34.184 --> 00:35.776
- Totally fine.
- After, you know--

00:35.928 --> 00:36.902
- I do know.

00:37.054 --> 00:38.537
- I want you
to understand that--

00:38.688 --> 00:40.781
- Fantasies and--yeah, yeah.

00:40.857 --> 00:42.933
I got it the first time.
- Oh, okay.

00:42.935 --> 00:44.877
- You mind if I
open the door now?

00:45.028 --> 00:46.361
- Please do.

00:46.380 --> 00:50.365
I'm gonna be up there
at my greeting spot.

00:50.442 --> 00:51.441
Okay.

00:51.460 --> 00:55.796
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

00:55.948 --> 00:57.948
- Everything okay
between you two?

00:57.966 --> 00:59.132
- Of course.

00:59.209 --> 01:02.394
- Just seemed
a little awkward.

01:02.546 --> 01:05.230
- Oh, look, our guest is here.
- Oh.

01:06.642 --> 01:07.958
- There you go.
- Ooh!

01:07.960 --> 01:09.793
- You okay?
- Yeah, I'm good.

01:09.812 --> 01:11.478
Just a little queasy.

01:11.572 --> 01:12.554
Happens every time I fly.

01:12.648 --> 01:14.740
- Hmm.
- Okay. That way?

01:14.817 --> 01:16.633
- Right there.
- Okay.

01:16.652 --> 01:17.968
Thanks.
- You're welcome.

01:17.986 --> 01:19.486
- Hi, Miss Marshall.

01:19.563 --> 01:21.896
I'm your host, Elena Roarke,
and this is my associate Ruby.

01:21.957 --> 01:23.807
- Welcome to Fantasy Island.

01:23.809 --> 01:25.492
- I think I'm gonna throw up.

01:25.644 --> 01:26.585
- Oh.
- Oh.

01:26.662 --> 01:27.920
<i> [playful music]</i>

01:27.996 --> 01:30.071
- Small sips.
- Thanks.

01:30.132 --> 01:32.257
- Sorry, it's just like
planes, trains, automobiles,

01:32.334 --> 01:34.835
they all make me feel
kind of green.

01:34.987 --> 01:36.595
I'm more of a horses, bicycles,

01:36.746 --> 01:38.155
foot kind of person, you know?

01:38.173 --> 01:41.082
- Well, how about you
take a seat right on he--

01:41.160 --> 01:42.601
oh.
- Oh, wow.

01:42.678 --> 01:43.844
- Oh, okay.

01:43.996 --> 01:46.163
We actually have rocks
on the island.

01:46.165 --> 01:47.606
You didn't need
to bring your own.

01:47.833 --> 01:50.016
Golly.
- I'm sorry. It's books.

01:50.018 --> 01:52.427
Edith Wharton, Jane Austen.

01:52.504 --> 01:53.779
R.S. Coldwater is my favorite.

01:53.930 --> 01:56.857
I'm obsessed; I'm the girl
who's had her nose in a book

01:56.933 --> 01:58.967
ever since elementary school.

01:58.969 --> 02:00.768
I even managed
to make reading my job.

02:00.846 --> 02:02.287
I'm a copy editor.

02:02.439 --> 02:03.847
- So tell me, Miss Marshall,

02:03.866 --> 02:05.849
what can the island do for you?

02:05.851 --> 02:07.442
- I need to get a life.

02:07.461 --> 02:10.854
And I need to get my nose
out of books.

02:10.873 --> 02:12.689
And I've tried before,
but the world

02:12.691 --> 02:14.782
is--it's so much.

02:14.860 --> 02:18.028
And books are where
I feel safe.

02:18.046 --> 02:19.863
- You don't feel safe
in the real world?

02:19.956 --> 02:22.532
- I feel out of step.

02:22.551 --> 02:23.976
Like I don't really belong.

02:24.127 --> 02:27.053
And I'm worried my whole life
is one big, "No, thank you."

02:27.130 --> 02:28.480
And I want it to be a yes.

02:28.632 --> 02:31.466
I--
[sighs]

02:31.543 --> 02:33.894
So I guess that's my fantasy,
to have the courage

02:33.970 --> 02:38.215
to say yes to real life,

02:38.233 --> 02:40.826
whatever that is,
not just life in books.

02:40.903 --> 02:43.871
- Real life
can be intimidating.

02:43.980 --> 02:45.313
And getting lost
in a good book,

02:45.391 --> 02:47.057
I mean, shoot,
there's nothing better,

02:47.150 --> 02:51.228
especially if it's romance.
[chuckles]

02:51.230 --> 02:53.821
- You ever read R.S. Coldwater?
- Mm-mm.

02:53.841 --> 02:57.751
- Okay. Okay.

02:57.903 --> 02:59.085
These are the Agnes novels.

02:59.238 --> 03:01.405
That's book one of three.
Start there.

03:01.423 --> 03:02.830
I got introduced to these
my freshman year of college.

03:02.908 --> 03:06.000
And Agnes is the first woman
I ever fell in love with.

03:06.020 --> 03:08.854
- Really?
- Yeah.

03:09.005 --> 03:10.189
- What was it about her?

03:10.265 --> 03:14.175
- She's independent
and strong and so smart.

03:14.195 --> 03:16.770
She wears breeches
and men's shirts.

03:16.846 --> 03:19.089
Just does whatever she wants.

03:19.091 --> 03:21.200
- Sounds like
my kind of woman.

03:23.929 --> 03:26.521
You'll need this.

03:26.540 --> 03:27.689
Here you go.

03:27.766 --> 03:29.750
Follow me, please.

03:32.955 --> 03:35.772
Say yes, Miss Marshall.

03:35.774 --> 03:37.591
- Okay.

03:39.778 --> 03:42.779
- Your fantasy begins now.

03:42.781 --> 03:43.964
Mm.

03:44.116 --> 03:46.558
<i> [bright music]</i>

03:46.635 --> 03:50.020
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

03:53.567 --> 03:55.734
[gasps, laughs]

03:55.811 --> 03:58.737
[indistinct chatter]

03:58.814 --> 04:01.740
<i> [soft chamber music]</i>

04:01.817 --> 04:09.039
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

04:16.982 --> 04:18.757
- You look lost.

04:18.984 --> 04:20.217
Can I help you?

04:22.429 --> 04:23.653
- Are you Agnes?

04:23.672 --> 04:26.080
- You must be a fan
of my husband's work.

04:26.158 --> 04:28.392
I'm Rachel Coldwater.

04:30.437 --> 04:32.604
<i> [dreamy music]</i>

04:32.756 --> 04:39.987
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

04:43.284 --> 04:45.859
- You're Rachel Coldwater?

04:45.935 --> 04:49.288
I'm--what? Wow!

04:49.364 --> 04:51.939
- Whoever you are,
you're very American.

04:52.034 --> 04:54.351
- Sorry.
Am I supposed to curtsy or--

04:54.353 --> 04:55.460
- Please.

04:55.612 --> 04:58.213
Women keep their heads
held high around here.

04:59.082 --> 05:01.300
- Oh.
- May I?

05:05.955 --> 05:09.049
Good heavens. Reggie.

05:09.125 --> 05:10.142
- What is it, darling?

05:10.293 --> 05:11.718
I was just getting
to the punch line.

05:11.795 --> 05:13.553
- This is your cousin Isabel.

05:13.630 --> 05:15.314
She's come all the way
from New York.

05:15.465 --> 05:17.983
- Your cousin?
Yes, I mean that's right.

05:18.060 --> 05:20.060
I am--I am your cousin
from New York.

05:20.154 --> 05:21.394
- Yes.

05:21.563 --> 05:23.971
Why, you were three years old
last time I saw you.

05:23.991 --> 05:25.657
Oh, this calls
for a fresh round of drinks.

05:25.734 --> 05:26.974
Let me just get Winnie.

05:26.994 --> 05:28.660
You know, I swear
I spend half of my time

05:28.737 --> 05:29.661
trying to find the maid.

05:29.738 --> 05:31.555
Just hold on.

05:31.557 --> 05:32.998
- [laughs]

05:33.149 --> 05:35.408
- How long can you stay for,
cousin?

05:35.561 --> 05:36.543
- I have no idea.

05:37.896 --> 05:39.729
Do you also write,
Mrs. Coldwater?

05:39.748 --> 05:42.232
- Oh, yes. All the time.

05:42.234 --> 05:45.159
Invitations to tea,
list for the market,

05:45.179 --> 05:48.421
thank you notes
for invitations to tea.

05:48.574 --> 05:49.497
Come.

05:49.591 --> 05:51.741
Let me introduce you
to our friends.

05:51.760 --> 05:54.519
<i> [lively percussive music]</i>

05:54.671 --> 05:57.189
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

05:57.340 --> 06:00.550
- Brian Cole. Hmm.
Right on time.

06:00.552 --> 06:03.695
- Finding the spot
wasn't exactly a challenge.

06:03.847 --> 06:06.031
- Elena Roarke, your host.

06:06.258 --> 06:09.092
So tell me, Mr. Cole,
what can the island do for you?

06:09.111 --> 06:10.276
- Ah.

06:10.520 --> 06:13.038
My fantasy is to experience
the ultimate physical

06:13.189 --> 06:16.023
and mental challenge
and overcome it, hopefully.

06:16.101 --> 06:18.710
- Hopefully?
- I'm an extreme survivalist.

06:18.937 --> 06:20.770
The uncertainty
is part of the fun.

06:20.772 --> 06:22.029
My wife never saw it that way.

06:22.107 --> 06:24.365
Ex-wife. I just got divorced.

06:24.385 --> 06:26.443
She thought I had
an unhealthy obsession.

06:26.536 --> 06:29.112
I saw it as a normal
human drive to excel.

06:29.114 --> 06:30.722
- Why Fantasy Island?

06:30.799 --> 06:32.282
There's tougher terrain
out there.

06:32.300 --> 06:34.784
- It's all been conquered.
Most of it by me.

06:34.803 --> 06:36.803
I want to be tested in ways
I never have been before.

06:36.955 --> 06:38.955
- I like your confidence,
Mr. Cole.

06:38.974 --> 06:41.048
- Give me your worst.
I can take it.

06:41.126 --> 06:43.193
Please hand over your gear.

06:45.313 --> 06:47.722
- You want my boots?
- Unnecessary.

06:47.799 --> 06:50.892
There's a machete
a little ways up the trail.

06:50.911 --> 06:52.802
You'll have no other tools.

06:52.804 --> 06:54.638
I'll see you on the other side.

06:54.640 --> 06:56.206
- All right.

06:57.809 --> 06:59.492
Hey, whatever
happens out there,

06:59.645 --> 07:00.977
no help, no rescue.

07:00.996 --> 07:02.421
- No problem.

07:02.497 --> 07:05.498
[birds chirping]

07:05.651 --> 07:08.427
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

07:08.578 --> 07:13.823
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:14.601 --> 07:17.010
<i> - Reginald, Rachel, thank you</i>
<i> so much for having me.</i>

07:17.086 --> 07:19.104
This has been amazing.

07:19.181 --> 07:23.516
Wait, you're both R. Coldwater.

07:23.593 --> 07:25.277
- Yes, well, we like to match
whenever possible.

07:25.353 --> 07:27.929
That's why she wears trousers,
you know.

07:27.948 --> 07:29.856
- Just like Agnes.

07:29.933 --> 07:32.242
Those novels changed my life.

07:34.788 --> 07:36.696
- All right.

07:36.773 --> 07:38.623
Good night, wife.

07:38.700 --> 07:39.958
Sleep well, dear cousin.

07:40.035 --> 07:41.367
I'll see you in the morning.

07:41.444 --> 07:42.461
- Good night.

07:45.874 --> 07:47.799
- How?

07:47.876 --> 07:49.283
- What?

07:49.303 --> 07:52.787
- How did the Agnes novels
change your life?

07:52.864 --> 07:57.717
- Oh, well, they just
showed me who I really was,

07:57.794 --> 08:00.220
and that love was so much more

08:00.372 --> 08:03.356
than I could ever
possibly imagine.

08:03.466 --> 08:05.875
- Reginald will be very pleased
to hear that.

08:05.877 --> 08:07.377
- Oh.

08:07.395 --> 08:13.825
But words on the page can't
compare to beating hearts

08:14.052 --> 08:16.310
and warm breath

08:16.330 --> 08:20.223
and the blood coursing
through one's veins.

08:20.242 --> 08:22.667
This is your room, cousin.

08:22.819 --> 08:25.745
<i> [soft music]</i>

08:25.822 --> 08:29.916
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

08:30.068 --> 08:31.918
- I'm sorry. I--[laughs]

08:31.995 --> 08:34.070
I don't normally do
that kind of thing.

08:34.089 --> 08:35.421
- You never kissed
a woman before?

08:35.574 --> 08:41.928
- I'm usually the--the kissee,
not the kisser.

08:42.005 --> 08:45.006
I'm just trying new things.
[laughs]

08:45.083 --> 08:48.009
- Well, you surprise me,
Isabel.

08:48.086 --> 08:50.695
And that doesn't happen
very often.

08:52.533 --> 08:54.758
Have a restful sleep.

08:54.760 --> 08:59.929
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

08:59.931 --> 09:02.599
<i> [tense percussive music]</i>

09:02.601 --> 09:06.452
- 181, 182, 183.

09:06.605 --> 09:07.546
Ooh.
[laughs]

09:07.773 --> 09:09.548
Almost a record.

09:09.699 --> 09:16.555
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:28.885 --> 09:30.810
Who's out there?

09:30.887 --> 09:31.886
Hello?

09:31.963 --> 09:35.323
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:37.152 --> 09:40.394
<i> [soft mysterious music]</i>

09:40.414 --> 09:47.335
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

10:15.023 --> 10:17.282
- Two manuscripts?

10:18.785 --> 10:20.785
Written in different hands?

10:20.862 --> 10:23.847
[footsteps approaching]

10:23.865 --> 10:31.129
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

10:48.631 --> 10:50.297
[loud thud]
[gasps]

10:50.375 --> 10:51.816
- What are you doing here,
cousin?

10:51.968 --> 10:53.652
- I knew it!
I knew it was you.

10:53.728 --> 10:56.045
This is so cool!

10:56.047 --> 10:59.324
You're R.S. Coldwater!

11:03.405 --> 11:04.904
- You don't know what you're
talking about, cousin.

11:05.056 --> 11:06.981
- Uh, the ink
on your fingertips,

11:07.000 --> 11:08.816
the duplicate manuscripts.

11:08.835 --> 11:11.077
Reginald obviously
copies your work

11:11.154 --> 11:13.838
and then takes all the credit.

11:13.990 --> 11:15.064
I always knew
that the Agnes novels

11:15.083 --> 11:16.508
could not have been written
by a man,

11:16.659 --> 11:19.052
and I was right, wasn't I?

11:20.755 --> 11:23.181
Rachel, you can trust me.

11:25.668 --> 11:26.851
- No one can learn about this.

11:27.003 --> 11:28.836
- But it's wrong for Reggie
to take credit.

11:28.914 --> 11:30.914
- He's not taking anything.

11:30.932 --> 11:33.191
I gave it to him.

11:33.268 --> 11:34.751
Ours is a marriage
of convenience.

11:34.753 --> 11:35.860
I asked him to marry me.

11:36.012 --> 11:39.013
I asked him to become
R.S. Coldwater.

11:39.032 --> 11:40.273
It was the only way
that I could gain access

11:40.425 --> 11:41.925
to London's best publisher.

11:41.943 --> 11:44.777
- Walsh and Sons.
- You know them?

11:44.930 --> 11:46.020
- Just their Wikipedia page.

11:46.097 --> 11:47.021
- Then you know
that they don't publish

11:47.098 --> 11:48.281
any female authors.

11:48.433 --> 11:49.874
No reputable publisher does.

11:50.026 --> 11:54.120
If Edmund Walsh
finds out about this,

11:54.197 --> 11:55.788
Agnes will be pulled
from the shelves,

11:55.941 --> 11:57.048
and we could lose our contract.

11:57.200 --> 12:01.444
If you love my work
like you say you do,

12:01.446 --> 12:03.888
then you must keep this quiet.

12:03.965 --> 12:06.741
<i> [dramatic music]</i>

12:06.818 --> 12:14.123
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

12:14.401 --> 12:16.192
- As you wish.

12:18.813 --> 12:20.196
- Thank you.

12:21.575 --> 12:24.409
<i> [lively percussive music]</i>

12:24.560 --> 12:30.415
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

12:31.826 --> 12:35.144
- [groaning]

12:35.146 --> 12:37.313
- Whoever you are,
I just saved your life.

12:37.332 --> 12:40.666
Drinking from that pond,
you can get dysentery.

12:40.819 --> 12:41.760
Stand up.

12:41.836 --> 12:45.655
<i> [inquisitive music]</i>

12:45.657 --> 12:47.098
Oh, my God.

12:49.269 --> 12:50.310
- What?

12:51.772 --> 12:54.189
- You're me.

13:00.263 --> 13:02.930
- So what are you writing?

13:02.949 --> 13:06.934
- Since you asked,
it's a love scene.

13:06.953 --> 13:09.012
- Oh, tell me.

13:09.030 --> 13:13.274
- Well, Agnes
is engaged to George.

13:13.368 --> 13:17.796
But she's just met
the very dashing Mr. Hall.

13:17.872 --> 13:21.282
In this scene,
Agnes and Mr. Hall

13:21.359 --> 13:24.861
are walking through
a field, and--

13:24.879 --> 13:27.288
- They get caught in the rain.

13:27.365 --> 13:30.383
- Yes. How did you know that?
[laughs]

13:30.535 --> 13:33.703
Have you had your cheeky
little nose in my notebook?

13:33.721 --> 13:36.297
You have, haven't you?

13:36.299 --> 13:40.134
Well, did you like it?

13:40.211 --> 13:42.362
- I had to read it
with one hand.

13:44.807 --> 13:46.407
- [chuckles]
Oh.

13:48.662 --> 13:51.404
<i> [soft suggestive music]</i>

13:51.480 --> 13:55.908
And what were you doing
with the other hand?

13:56.061 --> 14:01.005
Was it something like this?

14:04.845 --> 14:10.406
- It was more
like this, actually.

14:10.408 --> 14:14.835
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

14:14.929 --> 14:17.355
- Well, that's good to know.

14:21.936 --> 14:24.195
[footsteps approaching]

14:25.699 --> 14:27.031
Oh.

14:29.035 --> 14:30.109
[laughs]

14:30.203 --> 14:32.929
- I should probably
put these in water.

14:32.931 --> 14:38.293
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

14:42.698 --> 14:44.198
Oh, my God. Hi!

14:44.217 --> 14:45.958
Wait, you're here?
I'm not ready to leave yet.

14:46.111 --> 14:48.869
- I'm just checking in.
It's okay.

14:48.889 --> 14:51.556
And I must say,
this time suits you.

14:51.707 --> 14:53.057
You're practically glowing.

14:53.134 --> 14:55.801
- Well, I do feel
at home here.

14:55.896 --> 14:57.878
And I've been
quite the adventuress.

14:57.898 --> 14:59.564
Do you know that Rachel
is R.S. Coldwater?

14:59.715 --> 15:02.758
- I hope she inspires you
to drive your own story

15:02.810 --> 15:04.551
instead of living
inside another.

15:04.629 --> 15:07.906
- Well, she definitely
is inspiring.

15:08.057 --> 15:11.651
I'm really living.
But it is kind of frightening.

15:11.727 --> 15:15.204
- Is it possible that you need
to say yes to the fear?

15:16.082 --> 15:17.473
- [sighs]

15:17.492 --> 15:20.326
- You need to put those
in water before they wilt.

15:20.420 --> 15:22.420
- Yes.

15:22.571 --> 15:23.546
Bye.
- Bye.

15:25.483 --> 15:26.816
- You know, you could
have found a better way

15:26.834 --> 15:27.908
to introduce yourself.

15:27.986 --> 15:29.910
- You stole my machete.

15:30.004 --> 15:31.763
- Well, technically,
it's as much mine

15:31.839 --> 15:34.223
as it is yours, since I'm you.

15:34.935 --> 15:36.826
You sure I'm you?

15:36.919 --> 15:38.752
- Quite sure.

15:38.830 --> 15:40.163
- Could be worse.

15:40.165 --> 15:43.090
- Gee, thanks.
All right, listen, little me--

15:43.168 --> 15:44.943
- I'm average sized for my age.

15:45.019 --> 15:46.760
- Do you want to survive this
to make it back home?

15:46.838 --> 15:48.112
- Duh.

15:48.189 --> 15:49.948
Are you always this unfriendly?

15:50.024 --> 15:52.766
- I don't like you. Never have.

15:52.844 --> 15:56.212
- What? Why not?
No, I'm pretty awesome.

15:56.214 --> 15:57.438
- Okay, I've got my reasons.

15:57.515 --> 15:58.790
If we're gonna get
out of here, you need to do

15:58.866 --> 16:00.533
everything
exactly as I tell you,

16:00.685 --> 16:02.034
including
letting me concentrate.

16:02.128 --> 16:03.277
That clear?

16:03.371 --> 16:05.855
- Look, I might be you,
but I'm not a moron.

16:05.857 --> 16:08.782
<i> [inquisitive music]</i>

16:08.860 --> 16:10.284
Okay, okay, truce.

16:10.303 --> 16:14.288
Look, if we're gonna do this,
can we try to get along?

16:14.365 --> 16:15.974
I mean, we are family,
after all,

16:16.125 --> 16:18.125
with, like,
everything in common.

16:18.203 --> 16:21.062
- Would you please
stop talking?

16:22.983 --> 16:25.708
- I'm growing on you.
Oh, come on, admit it.

16:25.801 --> 16:27.986
- And get rid of that absurd
windbreaker, would you?

16:28.062 --> 16:30.363
It's the exact opposite
of camouflage.

16:34.402 --> 16:36.828
- You know, I won that
doing the running man

16:36.830 --> 16:39.813
in Northville Has Talent '91,
so.

16:39.833 --> 16:41.833
Or don't you remember?

16:41.984 --> 16:44.669
- No, I don't.

16:44.746 --> 16:48.564
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

16:48.583 --> 16:52.068
- Ooh. Aces high.
You now owe me 20.

16:52.070 --> 16:53.753
- Nicely done, cousin.
- Mm-hmm.

16:53.847 --> 16:55.680
- Can't you think of
something else to do, Reggie?

16:55.831 --> 16:57.573
She's going to go broke.

16:57.592 --> 16:58.924
- I've gone hunting.

16:59.077 --> 17:03.062
And I've napped twice.
What else is there to do? Hmm?

17:04.265 --> 17:07.600
- Ah, there you are,
Mr. Coldwater.

17:07.694 --> 17:10.677
<i> [tense music]</i>

17:10.697 --> 17:12.513
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

17:12.607 --> 17:13.865
Mrs. Coldwater.

17:13.941 --> 17:15.349
- Mr. Walsh.
What a delightful surprise.

17:15.368 --> 17:16.108
It's all right, Winnie.

17:16.277 --> 17:18.110
This is my brilliant publisher.

17:18.187 --> 17:20.279
- Mr. Walsh, I'm sorry
that I'm dressed so casually.

17:20.431 --> 17:21.855
I've just been out riding.

17:21.875 --> 17:26.151
- Ah. And who's this?
- Yes.

17:26.229 --> 17:28.954
Let me introduce
my cousin Isabel from America.

17:29.031 --> 17:31.307
Ah, Isabel, Edmund Walsh.

17:31.309 --> 17:32.958
- The foremost publisher
of Victorian literature.

17:33.035 --> 17:36.203
I'm well aware.
- Oh, aren't you charming?

17:36.222 --> 17:38.964
- To what do we owe the visit?
- Business in Paris.

17:39.117 --> 17:42.134
But I thought I'd stop by
and hand deliver your contract.

17:42.287 --> 17:44.120
We have some things to discuss.

17:44.122 --> 17:46.731
- Ah. Well, we're much obliged.

17:46.808 --> 17:48.733
- And can you stay for dinner?

17:48.884 --> 17:50.960
- Oh, yes. I'd planned on it.

17:50.962 --> 17:52.719
And I think I'll spend
the night too.

17:52.797 --> 17:56.032
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

17:59.061 --> 18:01.137
- [grunts]
When do we eat?

18:01.230 --> 18:04.231
All right, and I don't mean
lizards or roaches.

18:04.250 --> 18:06.400
I mean something
we can put on a bun.

18:06.477 --> 18:09.420
- There's a great pizza place
just over the next ridge.

18:09.572 --> 18:11.981
- Ha, ha.

18:11.999 --> 18:14.150
You know,
one thing I gotta know.

18:14.152 --> 18:18.154
Did we ever go on a date
with Hope Emory?

18:18.172 --> 18:19.413
- Yeah.

18:19.657 --> 18:20.914
- That should have been
the first thing you told me.

18:20.934 --> 18:23.676
Hey, way to go.

18:23.770 --> 18:25.394
- We even get married.

18:26.998 --> 18:28.848
- Yes! Oh, my God!

18:29.000 --> 18:30.942
My--my head just exploded.

18:31.093 --> 18:33.853
Well, we've definitely
gotta survive now.

18:33.929 --> 18:36.405
- Don't get too excited.
We're divorced.

18:38.434 --> 18:42.011
- You married our dream woman
and you blew it?

18:42.029 --> 18:43.788
- Well, I didn't blow it,
all right?

18:43.939 --> 18:45.623
Relationships are complicated.

18:45.700 --> 18:47.366
- You think I don't know that?

18:47.443 --> 18:49.702
We're the child of divorce.

18:49.796 --> 18:51.963
Did you really expect
a goddess like Hope Emory

18:52.156 --> 18:54.298
to just hang around while you--

18:54.375 --> 18:57.635
you spent months off in Borneo
living off cockroaches?

18:57.712 --> 18:58.970
All the things we wanted to do,

18:59.046 --> 19:01.180
the future we dreamed of.

19:02.367 --> 19:04.976
What happened to me
to become you?

19:05.127 --> 19:06.051
Get away from--
- Whoa.

19:06.128 --> 19:09.555
- Whoa!
[yells]

19:09.649 --> 19:10.982
[groans]

19:11.133 --> 19:12.875
- Dude! Dude, are you okay?

19:12.877 --> 19:14.710
- No. Not okay.

19:14.729 --> 19:16.154
[groans]

19:22.387 --> 19:23.977
- [groans]

19:23.997 --> 19:27.056
- Hold on. I'm on my way.

19:27.149 --> 19:30.075
- Oh, take your time.
Not going anywhere.

19:30.228 --> 19:34.246
- Ouch. That can't feel good.

19:34.399 --> 19:35.080
- Roarke.

19:35.082 --> 19:35.989
Where'd you come from?

19:36.009 --> 19:37.324
- Well,
given the circumstances,

19:37.326 --> 19:39.068
I hope that you'll
change your mind

19:39.070 --> 19:40.511
about wanting to be rescued.

19:40.621 --> 19:41.921
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

19:42.073 --> 19:44.164
- Why would I do that?

19:44.166 --> 19:46.184
- The possibility
of death comes to mind.

19:46.260 --> 19:49.261
- Now you're starting to sound
like my ex-wife.

19:49.414 --> 19:51.856
- So she's also concerned
about your death wish.

19:51.933 --> 19:53.399
Why are you here, Brian?

19:54.936 --> 19:59.104
- Because being trapped
under this boulder

19:59.199 --> 20:02.091
with no idea whether I'm gonna
manage to crawl out of here

20:02.109 --> 20:04.702
is the purest state of being
there is.

20:06.264 --> 20:06.946
- Mm-hmm.

20:07.040 --> 20:08.280
- What, you don't believe me?

20:08.433 --> 20:11.116
- I'm almost there.
Hang on, buddy.

20:11.193 --> 20:14.361
- Maybe you'll discover
that some burdens

20:14.439 --> 20:16.172
can turn out to be gifts.

20:18.659 --> 20:20.301
- I'm here.

20:21.128 --> 20:24.447
<i> [bright classical music]</i>

20:24.465 --> 20:26.039
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

20:26.059 --> 20:28.059
- Thank you.
I can serve Mr. Walsh.

20:29.229 --> 20:33.138
- Miss Marshall,
will you be visiting London?

20:33.291 --> 20:36.550
I would be glad to show you
around our fair city.

20:36.627 --> 20:42.114
Unless, of course, you have
a beau who would be offended.

20:43.651 --> 20:46.577
- Well, there is someone.

20:46.729 --> 20:47.987
Tell me, Mr. Walsh,

20:48.081 --> 20:49.805
do you know Charles Dickens?

20:49.824 --> 20:53.642
- Ugh,
relentlessly ambitious fellow

20:53.661 --> 20:55.160
who doesn't sell as many books

20:55.313 --> 20:58.314
as Mr. Coldwater's
Agnes novels.

20:58.374 --> 20:59.482
- No.

20:59.650 --> 21:04.003
- However, I am afraid
the sales could plummet.

21:04.079 --> 21:07.932
There are some nasty rumors
going around.

21:08.009 --> 21:10.417
- I find it best
to ignore idle gossip.

21:10.436 --> 21:11.602
Don't you?

21:11.754 --> 21:15.922
- Some claim that you
are not the true author

21:16.000 --> 21:17.942
of the Agnes books,
Mr. Coldwater.

21:18.019 --> 21:19.852
- A jealous rival, no doubt.

21:19.928 --> 21:21.170
[all chuckle]

21:21.263 --> 21:26.191
- And there is speculation
that Mrs. Coldwater

21:26.344 --> 21:28.119
is the true writer.

21:28.270 --> 21:31.196
- I can hardly write
a proper recipe.

21:31.349 --> 21:33.273
Far less a novel.
- Oh, hush.

21:33.351 --> 21:36.035
You're very good
with your stitching, dear.

21:36.187 --> 21:37.870
It's pure slander, sir.

21:37.946 --> 21:39.330
<i> [tense music]</i>

21:39.482 --> 21:41.549
- Would you excuse me
for just one moment?

21:43.711 --> 21:45.044
- Tell me, Reggie,

21:45.120 --> 21:47.263
what happens
in the third Agnes book?

21:50.034 --> 21:53.385
- Well, I've not
quite finished it.

21:53.462 --> 21:56.314
- Oh, yes,
but you must have some sense

21:56.465 --> 22:00.876
of your characters
and their fate.

22:00.878 --> 22:07.158
For example, does Agnes intend
to marry Gerald in book three?

22:08.977 --> 22:11.662
- Well, Walsh, you don't
want me to ruin the surprise.

22:11.739 --> 22:14.147
- Does she marry Gerald
or not?

22:14.167 --> 22:16.983
- I believe you mean George,
not Gerald.

22:17.078 --> 22:18.151
And no, Mr. Coldwater
has decided

22:18.171 --> 22:21.246
that Agnes
does not marry George

22:21.399 --> 22:23.174
because she doesn't want
to be anyone's property.

22:23.325 --> 22:24.175
Right?

22:24.344 --> 22:27.327
- That's right.
Thank you, Isabel.

22:27.347 --> 22:31.090
- And how would you know that,
Miss Marshall?

22:31.242 --> 22:34.743
- Well, it's all right here
in distinctly male hand.

22:34.745 --> 22:37.021
Reggie has hired me
to be his proofreader.

22:37.098 --> 22:38.856
You're far too generous
with your commas.

22:39.007 --> 22:40.674
- I'll do better.

22:40.735 --> 22:44.445
- Intellect as well as beauty,
Miss Marshall.

22:46.090 --> 22:48.607
You're a revelation.

22:48.609 --> 22:50.109
[clears throat]

22:50.261 --> 22:55.188
Forgive me for taking us
down this unpleasant path.

22:55.266 --> 22:57.190
Had to be done.
- Mm.

22:57.210 --> 23:00.953
- Winnie, I believe it's time
for some more wine.

23:01.029 --> 23:02.529
- You can do this.

23:02.548 --> 23:04.382
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

23:04.458 --> 23:07.051
- [grunting]

23:07.128 --> 23:08.427
- Come on!

23:09.872 --> 23:11.555
- Yes! I did it.

23:11.632 --> 23:13.224
- Yeah.

23:14.969 --> 23:16.727
- Oh.
- What?

23:18.623 --> 23:21.065
- It's--it's not like
I can see bone, but--

23:22.793 --> 23:25.461
Holy crap. Holy crap.
Holy crap.

23:25.479 --> 23:26.720
I can see bone.

23:26.739 --> 23:28.464
Sounds like
a compound fracture,

23:28.466 --> 23:32.410
which means I've got about six
hours before sepsis sets in.

23:32.561 --> 23:35.154
Then it's fever,
gangrene, and death.

23:35.230 --> 23:38.490
- No, no, no.
I can't--I can't do this.

23:38.643 --> 23:40.084
I cannot deal--

23:40.161 --> 23:44.163
- Hey, I'm depending on you
to survive this.

23:44.315 --> 23:47.967
Big breath in.
Slow breath out.

23:49.077 --> 23:53.246
Brian, I'm you,
and I'm telling you

23:53.324 --> 23:55.933
you're gonna
get me out of here.

23:56.084 --> 23:58.102
- I'm gonna get you
out of here.

23:58.329 --> 23:59.728
No man left behind.

24:04.426 --> 24:07.186
- Why is the lady of the house
doing manual labor?

24:07.262 --> 24:10.614
- You know by now
that I am no lady.

24:10.766 --> 24:14.118
I was just a criminal
destroying the evidence.

24:14.269 --> 24:17.362
- Then I'm complicit.
There's some ash here.

24:17.515 --> 24:20.975
- Thank you for your help
tonight with Walsh.

24:20.977 --> 24:24.962
- It was fun.
And you have to keep writing.

24:25.039 --> 24:28.632
- My books are where
I can truly be myself.

24:28.784 --> 24:31.026
I feel free when I write.

24:31.028 --> 24:32.285
- Then we're a good pair

24:32.363 --> 24:34.213
'cause I feel very free
when I read.

24:34.289 --> 24:36.198
- Wouldn't it be nice
if we could both

24:36.217 --> 24:38.959
just feel free all the time?

24:39.036 --> 24:41.479
<i> [soft romantic music]</i>

24:41.630 --> 24:47.026
When we met, you asked me
if I was Agnes.

24:48.546 --> 24:53.807
The truth is,
when I write, I am.

24:53.826 --> 24:56.035
- Liars!
- [gasps]

24:57.145 --> 24:59.221
- You'll never publish
another word.

24:59.223 --> 25:01.665
I'll see to it. You're through.

25:01.817 --> 25:04.460
<i> [dramatic music]</i>

25:07.898 --> 25:09.064
- Mr. Walsh. You misheard--

25:09.083 --> 25:12.325
- Enough, Miss Coldwater.

25:12.345 --> 25:14.512
I made it abundantly clear
that Walsh and Sons

25:14.663 --> 25:18.090
is only interested
in works of prestige.

25:18.242 --> 25:20.166
- So if a book is written
by a woman, it's foolish,

25:20.186 --> 25:22.244
but if it's written by a man,
it's genius?

25:22.263 --> 25:24.688
- I am rescinding
your contract,

25:24.840 --> 25:26.690
effective immediately.

25:26.842 --> 25:28.100
- Please don't do this.
I beg you.

25:28.252 --> 25:32.254
- Wait, you like brunettes,
don't you, Mr. Walsh?

25:32.273 --> 25:34.273
- I beg your pardon?

25:34.349 --> 25:37.426
- Martha Carrier,
she's a brunette, right?

25:37.444 --> 25:41.187
- I have no idea who that is.
- She's your mistress.

25:41.265 --> 25:43.949
You keep her in the slums
of St. Giles in an apartment

25:44.101 --> 25:46.769
that's barely big enough
for her and the children

25:46.771 --> 25:48.120
that you share together.

25:48.196 --> 25:50.455
It would just be a real shame
if your wife found out,

25:50.608 --> 25:51.957
and your readers.

25:52.109 --> 25:53.458
- You little bitch.

25:53.611 --> 25:55.277
How could you possibly
know that?

25:55.370 --> 25:57.112
- Oh, 'cause I can see
the future.

25:57.131 --> 25:58.463
And this is what's
gonna happen.

25:58.558 --> 26:02.968
You are going to continue
to publish the genius works

26:03.120 --> 26:06.972
of R.S. Coldwater,
to much wealth and acclaim,

26:07.066 --> 26:09.049
and you're gonna do right
by your mistress

26:09.068 --> 26:11.384
and dramatically improve
her living situation

26:11.404 --> 26:12.961
by giving her a new apartment

26:12.980 --> 26:16.799
and a salary of two pounds
a month.

26:16.817 --> 26:18.150
Does that sound good?

26:18.226 --> 26:20.578
- Five is more appropriate.
- Five pounds a month.

26:20.729 --> 26:21.970
<i> [tense music]</i>

26:21.989 --> 26:25.332
- I will leave
the signed contract upstairs.

26:27.086 --> 26:32.238
If you'll excuse me,
I have to pack my things.

26:32.316 --> 26:34.817
- It's lovely to see you,
Mr. Walsh.

26:34.835 --> 26:37.410
Come again soon.

26:37.430 --> 26:39.838
[both laugh]

26:39.990 --> 26:42.016
- [groans]
Ow, ow, ow.

26:44.328 --> 26:47.162
- No, I'm gonna
figure something out.

26:47.164 --> 26:50.182
- Until today, I thought
I had a handle on you.

26:50.334 --> 26:52.192
Now I'm realizing, not so much.

26:53.279 --> 26:55.020
Because I never thought
you were someone

26:55.172 --> 26:57.856
who could
face a situation like this

26:58.008 --> 26:59.491
without giving into the fear.

27:01.195 --> 27:03.245
- Yeah, me neither,
to be honest.

27:04.940 --> 27:09.201
- Maybe this is, uh, weird,
but...

27:09.277 --> 27:10.377
I'm proud of you.

27:13.132 --> 27:17.209
And by the way, you're right.

27:17.361 --> 27:21.697
It was all my fault,
the divorce.

27:21.715 --> 27:23.289
Of course Hope left.

27:23.367 --> 27:25.976
She couldn't make a life
with someone

27:26.203 --> 27:29.647
obsessed with proving himself
in all the wrong ways.

27:29.798 --> 27:32.724
<i> [sentimental music]</i>

27:32.877 --> 27:34.968
- Maybe she should have
tried harder

27:35.062 --> 27:37.363
to understand why you do that.

27:41.218 --> 27:43.886
You know what we need?
- Hmm?

27:43.904 --> 27:48.207
- A rock with a sharp edge
to use as a chisel.

27:49.894 --> 27:51.835
- Yeah, yeah.

27:51.987 --> 27:53.061
- I get you're feeling
nostalgic,

27:53.080 --> 27:55.747
but no running man
while I'm gone.

27:55.900 --> 27:57.424
- [chuckles]

28:07.094 --> 28:11.671
- Oh, my Victorian swoon. Oh!

28:11.691 --> 28:13.524
[both laughing]

28:13.600 --> 28:15.008
Did I get it?

28:15.085 --> 28:17.861
- It's dazzling.
- Oh, my gosh.

28:18.013 --> 28:20.531
I just started
the second Agnes novel.

28:20.682 --> 28:22.015
Oh, Elena, these books,

28:22.034 --> 28:24.927
I mean, really,
you should read them.

28:24.929 --> 28:27.095
- I don't have time to read,
sadly.

28:27.097 --> 28:30.023
- Well, I gotta admit,
I am so jealous of Isabel.

28:30.042 --> 28:32.192
I would love to be gallivanting

28:32.211 --> 28:35.954
around the countryside
with women in trousers.

28:36.031 --> 28:37.956
- You can galivant here,
you know,

28:38.108 --> 28:40.200
with whomever
you want to galivant.

28:40.294 --> 28:43.128
- I know. Someday.

28:43.205 --> 28:45.556
Thanks to women
like Rachel Coldwater.

28:45.632 --> 28:47.299
- [chuckles]
Yes.

28:47.451 --> 28:51.711
- Well, I am off to Agnes.

28:51.805 --> 28:56.433
Expect to see a "Do Not
Disturb" sign on my door.

28:56.510 --> 28:57.793
- Not a problem.

28:57.811 --> 29:00.796
<i> [soft inquisitive music]</i>

29:00.889 --> 29:04.390
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

29:04.410 --> 29:08.804
- Okay. Hmm.

29:08.806 --> 29:11.081
- Ahh!

29:11.233 --> 29:12.991
When do they invent
the hair tie?

29:13.068 --> 29:14.977
[knock on door]

29:14.995 --> 29:17.087
<i> [soft music]</i>

29:17.164 --> 29:18.905
I've made a knot of my hair.

29:18.924 --> 29:20.573
- Can I help you?

29:20.593 --> 29:26.913
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

29:26.932 --> 29:30.225
You see, it's--oh.
- There you go.

29:31.604 --> 29:34.679
- [sighs]
- Now, tell me.

29:34.756 --> 29:36.089
How did you know

29:36.108 --> 29:38.424
all of those things
about Walsh?

29:38.502 --> 29:41.003
- If I told you,
you would not believe me.

29:41.021 --> 29:44.022
- Well, you were magnificent.

29:44.099 --> 29:45.932
You are magnificent.

29:46.010 --> 29:47.284
- I was terrified.

29:47.361 --> 29:50.621
I couldn't let him silence you.

29:50.697 --> 29:53.106
- Your breathing is lively.
- Is it?

29:53.183 --> 29:55.775
These corsets are very tight.

29:55.795 --> 29:58.170
- I'll loosen it for you.
- Yes.

30:03.803 --> 30:04.951
[gasps]

30:05.029 --> 30:07.879
- Sorry.
I have to get some slack.

30:08.032 --> 30:11.550
- [breathing heavily]

30:11.626 --> 30:14.369
- Is that better?

30:14.371 --> 30:16.021
- Yes.

30:18.317 --> 30:19.358
Yes.

30:20.969 --> 30:23.487
<i> - ♪ Like a chain of light ♪</i>

30:23.638 --> 30:27.366
<i> ♪ Guiding me through</i>
<i> the darkest night ♪</i>

30:31.405 --> 30:33.405
- Do you ever think you were
born in the wrong time?

30:33.481 --> 30:34.906
<i> [gentle music]</i>

30:35.059 --> 30:37.392
- Not when I'm with you.
- Hmm.

30:37.411 --> 30:40.245
- Our hopes for the future,

30:40.322 --> 30:43.915
I wish I could be alive
to experience it.

30:44.068 --> 30:46.585
What about you?

30:46.737 --> 30:48.846
- Sometimes.

30:48.997 --> 30:50.681
But not today.

30:50.757 --> 30:54.634
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

30:54.745 --> 30:56.669
- I have to go.

30:56.689 --> 30:57.929
I need to get back to my room

30:58.082 --> 31:00.506
before Winnie comes home
from chapel.

31:00.526 --> 31:02.359
- [laughs]

31:08.942 --> 31:11.517
- What am I gonna do with you?

31:11.612 --> 31:12.703
- Whatever you want.

31:12.854 --> 31:20.043
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

31:21.955 --> 31:23.105
- Saying yes, are you?

31:23.198 --> 31:25.365
- Oh, my God.
How do you do that?

31:25.384 --> 31:27.943
- I hope you remember
this feeling later

31:27.961 --> 31:28.960
when you go back home.

31:29.113 --> 31:31.704
- How can I ever forget
this feeling?

31:31.724 --> 31:32.973
Look...

31:34.118 --> 31:36.635
Rachel doesn't belong here.

31:36.711 --> 31:37.895
I think she needs
to come back with me.

31:38.046 --> 31:39.045
She deserves to live in a place

31:39.123 --> 31:40.639
where she doesn't
have to hide.

31:40.715 --> 31:42.566
- So you want to bring
Rachel Coldwater

31:42.717 --> 31:45.193
back with you to the present?

31:46.554 --> 31:47.462
- Uh, yeah.

31:47.481 --> 31:48.463
- And you're asking this

31:48.632 --> 31:50.148
because it's in Rachel's
best interest,

31:50.300 --> 31:51.950
not because you're in love
with her

31:52.060 --> 31:53.577
and you don't want
to say goodbye?

31:53.728 --> 31:56.580
- Okay, hear me out.

31:56.731 --> 32:01.826
You, this place, Rachel,

32:01.979 --> 32:05.255
you're just all giving me
the courage to really live.

32:05.407 --> 32:08.316
And I just want
to keep doing that.

32:08.377 --> 32:10.076
With her.

32:10.095 --> 32:13.597
And I think that she wants
the same thing too.

32:13.748 --> 32:14.673
So what do you say?

32:14.749 --> 32:20.312
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

32:22.666 --> 32:24.799
- One sec.

32:24.835 --> 32:26.001
Oh, I'm--I'm sorry.

32:26.019 --> 32:28.946
I'm just getting to the end
of this chapter.

32:29.097 --> 32:30.855
Oh!
[chuckles]

32:31.008 --> 32:33.675
Okay. What's going on?

32:33.694 --> 32:35.285
- I have a job for you.

32:35.437 --> 32:36.328
- Ooh.

32:39.607 --> 32:42.275
- No. Not good.

32:42.352 --> 32:44.294
Ugh. It tastes of sulfur.

32:46.298 --> 32:48.114
- Sorry.

32:48.133 --> 32:50.258
I'll go find another stream.

32:53.472 --> 32:56.122
You know,
I--I just don't get it.

32:56.200 --> 32:57.866
What are we even doing
out here?

32:57.868 --> 33:00.310
Why would you put yourself
in situations like this

33:00.462 --> 33:01.870
over and over?

33:01.888 --> 33:04.272
I would never do this.

33:05.818 --> 33:07.209
So why do you?

33:07.227 --> 33:09.728
- You want to know?
I'll tell you.

33:09.880 --> 33:12.047
<i> [sentimental music]</i>

33:12.065 --> 33:14.899
You're in ninth grade, right?

33:14.901 --> 33:17.995
- Yeah. Two months in.
- Right.

33:18.146 --> 33:21.481
So not long from now,
a week after Thanksgiving,

33:21.500 --> 33:26.652
you'll be walking home,
minding your own business.

33:26.730 --> 33:27.653
Randy Boyle--

33:27.673 --> 33:29.006
- What, the dickweed who's made

33:29.157 --> 33:32.250
my life a misery
since elementary school?

33:32.327 --> 33:34.753
- Yeah, he and his buddies
pull you off the street,

33:34.905 --> 33:36.680
put you
in the trunk of his car.

33:36.831 --> 33:38.757
- Seriously?

33:38.833 --> 33:40.258
- And that's the fun part.

33:41.245 --> 33:43.336
They drive you out
to the Adirondack preserve,

33:43.355 --> 33:44.688
in the middle of nowhere,

33:44.839 --> 33:48.859
take your coat,
sneakers, socks.

33:49.010 --> 33:50.676
- In December?

33:50.738 --> 33:52.195
- They think it's hilarious.

33:52.347 --> 33:55.574
You just wander around
aimlessly for a while.

33:57.110 --> 33:59.611
But by morning,
you're hypothermic.

33:59.763 --> 34:01.872
- But I find my way out?

34:02.023 --> 34:03.932
- No, you get lucky.

34:03.950 --> 34:06.376
A hiker spots you eventually.

34:06.453 --> 34:11.864
But what's worse, when I was
dying out there in those woods,

34:11.884 --> 34:13.291
is the humiliation you feel

34:13.368 --> 34:16.536
when everyone looks at you
and just whispers.

34:16.555 --> 34:20.390
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

34:20.467 --> 34:23.042
- Oh, man.

34:23.120 --> 34:25.187
This is gonna be so bad.

34:27.399 --> 34:31.026
- I swore to myself
I'd never be that weak again.

34:31.978 --> 34:33.361
- That's why you hate me.

34:35.723 --> 34:37.157
Because I'm weak.

34:38.560 --> 34:39.943
- No.

34:40.019 --> 34:41.995
See, that's the point.

34:44.416 --> 34:45.749
You're not weak.

34:46.827 --> 34:48.126
I am.

34:49.663 --> 34:51.663
I thought I got over it.

34:51.757 --> 34:53.815
You know, put it behind me,
but I never did the work.

34:53.834 --> 34:56.242
I just buried it.

34:56.261 --> 35:00.079
Kept trying to prove to myself
that I wasn't you.

35:00.099 --> 35:02.057
- And that throws Hope away.

35:03.918 --> 35:05.060
Damn.

35:06.087 --> 35:08.605
- I never admitted that
to anyone.

35:08.756 --> 35:14.519
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

35:14.671 --> 35:16.029
And you know what?

35:17.524 --> 35:19.407
There's nothing wrong with you.

35:21.286 --> 35:25.163
You were just a kid, doing
the best you could, surviving.

35:27.108 --> 35:29.251
I'm sorry I was so hard on you.

35:30.704 --> 35:32.796
- Oh. No, no.

35:32.947 --> 35:34.706
It's okay, dude.

35:34.858 --> 35:37.709
[stammering]

35:37.861 --> 35:38.969
- I'm sorry.

35:39.045 --> 35:40.637
- We're gonna be fine.
We're gonna be fine.

35:40.864 --> 35:43.548
I promise.
We're gonna be fine.

35:43.700 --> 35:45.625
[crying]

35:45.702 --> 35:52.524
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

35:54.895 --> 35:56.486
- I'm having to return
to London

35:56.563 --> 35:58.229
in a couple of weeks.
- Mm-hmm.

35:58.323 --> 36:01.049
- I would love you
to come with me.

36:01.067 --> 36:03.994
- Hmm.
- What, is something wrong?

36:04.221 --> 36:06.404
Do you have to return
to America?

36:07.166 --> 36:12.002
- It's complicated,
but no, I can't stay.

36:12.153 --> 36:14.245
- When I first met you,

36:14.322 --> 36:17.582
I thought that my life
was complete.

36:17.659 --> 36:20.084
But now--

36:20.161 --> 36:24.255
now I can see
that I wasn't living.

36:24.332 --> 36:26.308
- I feel the same way.

36:29.913 --> 36:32.856
Wait, why don't you
come with me?

36:32.933 --> 36:36.193
- Isabel Marshall,
there you are.

36:36.344 --> 36:39.345
- Ruby, what a surprise!

36:39.364 --> 36:40.422
- Uh, Ruby is--

36:40.440 --> 36:43.366
- Oh, I'm a friend of Isabel's.
Hi.

36:43.518 --> 36:46.369
I'm delivering a speech
at an abolitionist conference

36:46.446 --> 36:47.946
in Vienna in a couple of days.

36:48.040 --> 36:50.022
So I hope you don't mind
me barging in.

36:50.100 --> 36:52.283
- Of course not.
You must stay for dinner.

36:52.360 --> 36:54.786
I will tell Reggie
that we've got one more guest.

36:54.862 --> 36:55.787
Excuse me.

36:55.863 --> 37:00.625
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

37:00.777 --> 37:03.611
- Roarke said no, didn't she?

37:03.630 --> 37:05.180
- Not exactly.

37:07.875 --> 37:09.284
You know,
I am so grateful for you

37:09.286 --> 37:12.954
for introducing me
to the Agnes novels.

37:12.956 --> 37:14.973
So many generations
paved the way

37:15.049 --> 37:19.069
so that you and I can be
whoever we want to be.

37:19.220 --> 37:24.557
You know, because they
were brave, we can be too.

37:24.634 --> 37:27.077
- You mean women like Rachel?

37:27.228 --> 37:30.747
- And if she's not here
to pave the way...

37:30.898 --> 37:33.491
- Then there won't be a road.

37:33.568 --> 37:37.128
- Well, less of one,
that's for sure.

37:39.666 --> 37:42.742
- So Rachel has to stay

37:42.761 --> 37:45.303
because her voice needs
to be heard here and now.

37:46.765 --> 37:48.974
- I'm so sorry.

37:50.010 --> 37:51.584
Do you want to say
goodbye first?

37:51.661 --> 37:53.085
- No.

37:53.105 --> 37:56.347
I don't think that I can.

37:56.500 --> 37:57.440
Let's just go.

38:04.024 --> 38:06.616
- Welcome back, Miss Marshall.

38:06.693 --> 38:09.677
<i> [apprehensive music]</i>

38:09.679 --> 38:11.037
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

38:14.034 --> 38:16.367
<i> [hopeful percussive music]</i>

38:16.520 --> 38:18.369
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

38:18.522 --> 38:20.705
- You survived, Mr. Cole.

38:20.782 --> 38:22.190
Ahead of schedule, no less.

38:22.192 --> 38:24.042
- I feel like I just
relived a lifetime.

38:24.194 --> 38:26.952
- I hope you felt
it was a gift, not a burden.

38:26.972 --> 38:28.972
- Oh, it was a huge gift.
Thank you.

38:28.974 --> 38:31.290
I'm gonna go home and see
if I can win her back.

38:31.310 --> 38:33.977
- Ah. Fingers crossed.
[chuckles]

38:34.128 --> 38:36.021
Oh! Okay.

38:37.149 --> 38:39.374
- That is for reintroducing me
to someone

38:39.376 --> 38:41.133
I'd never given a chance.

38:41.211 --> 38:44.045
Now we are friends
and living together.

38:44.064 --> 38:45.947
And that's all because of you.

38:46.825 --> 38:49.067
- Moments like this, Mr. Cole,

38:49.219 --> 38:51.886
are the reason I do what I do.

38:51.888 --> 38:56.574
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

38:56.726 --> 38:59.577
<i> [soft music]</i>

38:59.654 --> 39:02.914
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

39:03.066 --> 39:04.749
- Plane leaves in 15.

39:04.901 --> 39:06.234
- Yeah.

39:06.252 --> 39:10.405
- Guess we won't have
a storybook ending this time.

39:10.423 --> 39:12.924
- Isabel learned to say yes.

39:13.000 --> 39:15.000
That's what she was here to do.
Hmm?

39:15.020 --> 39:16.853
- I know, it just...
[sighs]

39:17.004 --> 39:19.731
Doesn't feel right,
though, does it?

39:21.860 --> 39:24.861
You know, I finished
the last Agnes novel.

39:24.938 --> 39:28.865
- How does it end?
- Hmm. With a surprise twist.

39:30.093 --> 39:32.443
After suddenly disappearing
from her life,

39:32.520 --> 39:37.448
Agnes's lover returns
to be with her forever.

39:37.601 --> 39:40.451
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

39:40.604 --> 39:44.381
<i> Agnes knew their time together</i>
<i> was drawing to a close.</i>

39:44.457 --> 39:47.108
<i> There was a chill</i>
<i> in the morning air now,</i>

39:47.127 --> 39:51.036
<i> and the peonies had dropped</i>
<i> their last blossoms.</i>

39:51.056 --> 39:53.038
<i> They said goodbye.</i>

39:53.116 --> 39:55.783
- Miss Marshall, it's time

39:55.802 --> 39:58.019
for the next chapter
of your story.

39:59.564 --> 40:03.625
- I was just remembering...

40:03.627 --> 40:05.568
<i> - A woman like Agnes,</i>

40:05.645 --> 40:10.073
<i> perhaps she was not deserving</i>
<i> of long-lasting love.</i>

40:10.224 --> 40:14.560
- You know, every guest should
leave Fantasy Island reborn,

40:14.579 --> 40:17.989
ready to live
their best true life.

40:18.141 --> 40:22.585
And I know that you found
your best life.

40:22.737 --> 40:24.812
- Yeah.

40:24.831 --> 40:26.814
- And it's not New York.

40:26.816 --> 40:30.485
<i> [uplifting music]</i>

40:30.503 --> 40:33.838
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

40:33.990 --> 40:35.990
- Wait, what are you saying?

40:35.992 --> 40:39.844
- Well, you can walk with me
to the plane,

40:39.996 --> 40:41.587
and you'll never
see Rachel again,

40:41.589 --> 40:46.443
or you can walk
through that door,

40:46.594 --> 40:49.654
and you'll become a part
of history forever.

40:49.731 --> 40:51.839
- I can go back?

40:51.858 --> 40:53.324
- If you say yes.

40:55.269 --> 40:56.769
- Take your time.
I know it's a big--

40:56.863 --> 40:58.696
- Yes, Roarke, yes!

40:58.848 --> 41:00.957
- [laughs]

41:01.034 --> 41:04.519
Well, then,
whenever you're ready.

41:04.537 --> 41:06.537
Go.

41:06.690 --> 41:08.781
- Like--
- Go.

41:08.800 --> 41:11.116
<i> - Agnes accepted her fate.</i>

41:11.136 --> 41:14.862
<i> She resigned herself</i>
<i> to solitude.</i>

41:14.881 --> 41:16.698
- Yes.

41:16.716 --> 41:23.730
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

41:28.228 --> 41:32.489
<i> - And then, from a distance,</i>
<i> she heard her name.</i>

41:32.565 --> 41:34.365
- Rachel!

41:42.000 --> 41:46.060
<i> - ♪ Light ♪</i>

41:46.062 --> 41:48.838
<i> ♪ In the skies all above so ♪</i>

41:48.915 --> 41:52.416
<i> ♪ High ♪</i>

41:52.569 --> 41:53.826
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

41:53.845 --> 41:56.571
<i> - Once again,</i>
<i> the flowers bloomed.</i>

41:56.573 --> 42:00.908
<i> Only this time,</i>
<i> it would be an endless summer.</i>

42:00.927 --> 42:03.853
- I knew you were a romantic.

42:04.005 --> 42:05.580
- Okay, sometimes.

42:05.598 --> 42:08.007
- Uh-huh.
[both laugh]

42:08.026 --> 42:10.527
[plane engine roaring]

42:10.678 --> 42:12.770
- Yes, yes. Yes.

42:12.922 --> 42:17.075
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

42:19.445 --> 42:19.911
<i> [dreamy music]</i>

42:22.448 --> 42:29.337
<i> ♪ ♪</i>
